Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do‭? ‬Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change‭? ‬Although in‭ ‬1917‭ ‬D’Arcy Thompson stated that‭ “‬Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms‭” ‬the same can be said today. More recently,‭ ‬mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny‭ (‬e.g.,‭ ‬Raup and Stanley,‭ ‬1981‭)‬. Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum,‭ ‬in combination with experimental studies,‭ ‬can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell‭ (‬Stone,‭ ‬1995‭)‬. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through‭ ‬360‭ ‬degrees of space.  These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls,‭ ‬which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis.  This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary,‭ ‬and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture.  In most shells,‭ ‬the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl‭ (‬body whorl‭)‬.  ‭ ‬The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical,‭ ‬basal,‭ ‬apertural and abapertural views. ‭(‬The‭ "‬usual‭" ‬orientation of a shell is an apertural view,‭ ‬with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.‭)‬

A method for counting whorls is seen below.  First,‭ ‬the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins.  A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts.  Whorls are counted from this line,‭ ‬and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes‭ (‬i.e. builds‭) ‬its shell.  It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented.  Once a mathematical formulation is made,‭ ‬it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia remained rather static for the last ten years.  While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015.  The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  That being said, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage).  In other words,  the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done.  In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.
	Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%.  The c-section rates additionally point to another concerning issue.  While the rate of c-section is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural.  This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country.  Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas.  Another issue of access concerns vertical equity.  There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.
	In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service.  Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child.  There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive.  Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results.  There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example).  In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs.  This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In my pursuit of a degree in social work, I aim to work in the Division of Family and Children Services, focusing on helping abused or neglected children, and supporting troubled families. The values I bring to the field include service, respect, ethical practice, commitment to strengthening relationships, and a dedication to professional growth to remain skilled. These are not just professional values; they are deeply personal to me.

Growing up, I've always desired to assist others, but I was uncertain about my career path. Throughout high school and college, I saw many people retreat from their problems in denial and some used coping strategies that weren't ideal. Witnessing these situations led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still undecided about my career, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. He was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police. To assist, I drove to his parents’ house, where I privately shared my concerns with the police. They asked me to speak with the parents, as they were powerless to intervene. When I questioned the parents about their son’s behavior, they seemed defensive and blamed him for involving outsiders in "simple" disputes. This experience sparked my interest in social work to help children with family conflicts.

Another crucial value for social work is social justice. Society claims to value individuals but often follows outdated traditions rather than embracing uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like everyone else? I am an individual and reject limiting myself to fit into others' molds. Throughout high school and college, I protested social injustice: I colored my hair unnatural colors, wore expressive clothing, pierced my ears beyond the norm, joined the GSBA, and fought against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against injustice.

This document explores the Biological and Sociocultural models in the context of insomnia. The Biological model delves into genetic factors and medical aspects that influence sleep disorders. On the other hand, the Sociocultural model investigates the environmental influences that relate to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review that follows examines these models and presents research that pertains to and elucidates them. The research findings are then critically evaluated to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

Insomnia, a sleep disorder, can be categorized as either a primary sleep disorder, one related to another mental disorder, or one stemming from medical conditions or substance use. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, while those related to mental disorders fall under Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). Other categories encompass sleep disorders due to medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias, which include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS), pertain to issues with initiating or maintaining sleep. Primary Insomnia, for instance, is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia refers to difficulty staying awake for at least a month. Parasomnias, on the other hand, involve sleep disorders linked to behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. These include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified.

The Biological model of sleep disorders centers on genes, inherited factors, and physiological aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus, containing orexin, regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study conducted on mice found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons that are specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep, while its inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time in mice (Matsuki et al., 2009). This suggests that animal models can be generalized to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A defect or absence of this receptor could alter one's ability to sleep adequately without medication. The Sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, it could regulate sleep. An alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual, negatively impacting aspects of life such as school, career, and everyday tasks that require focus.

This document delves into three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with a concise definition of the condition. It then outlines the diagnostic process, highlighting common symptoms, or "red flags." Lastly, it concludes with strategies for teachers working in mainstream classrooms to support students with CAPD.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is characterized by the inefficiency and ineffectiveness of the central nervous system (CNS) in utilizing auditory information. Simply put, it is a condition where the brain struggles to properly process sounds, distinguishing words from background noise, despite normal hearing. Individuals with CAPD can hear perfectly but face difficulties in the brain's processing of what they hear.

The earliest recorded mention of CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, initially referred to as "auditory imperception." Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for children with communicative disorders in 1954. Kimura introduced dichotic testing and explained the physiological basis of the central nervous system's role in dichotic perception in 1961. A 1977 national conference further stimulated research into CAPD.

CAPD presents in various forms, including difficulty in localizing sounds in space, distinguishing between sounds, recognizing sound patterns, detecting changes in speech, and synthesizing sound clues meaningfully. It can also manifest as a struggle to determine the sequence of auditory information.

Diagnosing CAPD involves a systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function. Professionals such as audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists use various measures to assess auditory-related skills. There is no single, consistently reliable test, and the cause of CAPD remains unknown. Tests typically present multiple auditory stimuli and ask for differentiation. Advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals in the ear and measuring responses.

Twelfth Night teaches that while disguise can be a powerful tool to maintain deception for extended periods, it ultimately requires the wearer to shed that false persona to prevent losing one's true self. The challenge lies in ending the charade, as it may lead to feelings of alienation. One must then choose between preserving self-identity or maintaining relationships. Some may accept the deception without issue, but others might be offended. The theme of gender role reversal in deception is complex, raising questions like why someone might feel the need to assume an opposite-gender guise. In Viola’s case, it's a form of self-defense: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249) Arriving in an unfamiliar land, Viola masquerades as a man to safeguard herself from potential threats. Her scheme works, but it isolates her from the female community, and she finds herself in a romantic turmoil with Olivia and Orsino: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261) While this could be seen as progressive, to a modern reader, Twelfth Night might demonstrate how deception can help uncover suppressed emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. Unshed feelings may be forced to the surface due to Viola/Cesario's presence. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario because she thinks he's a man, or does she secretly harbor affection for women? It seems unlikely, as Olivia's character seems to mock those who judge others solely on appearance. This is evident in her quick shift from Cesario to Sebastian, and her familial acceptance of Cesario/Viola: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has long been criticized for its harshness, notably in the case of the Ovaherero and Nama genocide in German South West Africa. However, it's crucial to note that a broad colonial empire like Germany's cannot be defined by such a singular description. The empire's policies and administration varied greatly across its diverse geography. Educational systems also differed significantly. After taking over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, the British found a well-educated African population. Similarly, contemporary authors praised German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies. Yet, the situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) starkly contrasted this. Unlike in East Africa, where the state played a key role in educating natives, in South West Africa, the responsibility largely fell to missionary societies with limited government support. The German government heavily invested in European education, establishing state schools and supporting missionary schools. These policies had lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted educated African populations, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to this disparity. This paper aims to explore these factors, especially new research on settlers' and colonial authorities' attitudes towards native Africans.

Many sources discuss education in the German colonial empire, most in German and written during or shortly after the colonial period. Early works mainly described educational systems, while later English works expanded on these discussions through comparisons and detailed analyses. These studies highlighted significant variations in educational systems across colonies. Notably, Cohen's study compared educational systems in South West Africa and East Africa, attributing differences to South West Africa's large settler population.

South West Africa's climate was generally more temperate than other German colonies, with much of the territory being desert. The European population reflected this, with nearly 15,000 whites in South West Africa by 1913, compared to only 5,336 in the next largest settler colony, East Africa.

The landscape of Popular Music has evolved significantly over the past century, leading to a vast array of genres, with each having numerous sub and sub-sub genres. For instance, rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk have all given birth to various sub-genres. Within this expansive canvas, Heavy Metal rock has stood out, becoming one of the most expressive and diverse genres in the past four decades. Its diversity stems from its early realization of flexibility, inspiring the creation of numerous sub-genres that continue to multiply today.

Today, the heavy metal scene is so fragmented that defining what 'heavy metal' truly is can be challenging. It has absorbed themes from various other genres, yet its roots remain in a movement characterized by darkness. Metal is often described as a 'music of more'—more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatricality. Musicians in this genre are highly skilled, showcasing their instrumental prowess in their music. Additionally, the genre has a strong connection to drug culture, notably driven by the psychedelic boom of the mid-70s. This movement reflects many dark, visceral qualities, which were relatively new to popular music at the time. Later generations of metal bands have also drawn inspiration from the Romantic Era's darker themes. Lyrics, like the ones from "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles, exemplify this darkness:

"Helter Skelter," a song by The Beatles, exhibits the genre's darker side, portraying the ups and downs supposedly inspired by drug use. This track is considered one of the first heavy metal songs, responding to a heavier, darker song by The Rolling Stones. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate their ability to create a similarly intense sound, which they achieved with "Helter Skelter."

Before the Surrealists began painting their dreamlike works, Henri Rousseau was already crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the Post-Impressionist artist, showcases not just a woman in awe of a dream landscape, but also Rousseau’s personal dreams and goals as a painter. He yearned for recognition, acceptance, and praise from the art world he admired, but faced an internal dilemma: conform to mimic established styles to gain acceptance, or remain creatively independent and unique. The Dream is the painting that best embodies this lifelong struggle in Rousseau’s career.

To understand The Dream through this lens, one must first know Rousseau's story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France, he was a tinsmith's son who grew up without formal art training. He worked as a gabelou until his forties and pursued painting as a source of comfort after the deaths of his wife and infant children. Unlike his contemporaries, Rousseau was a folk painter, driven by the hopes and dreams of the average working class.

Rousseau’s ambition to gain acceptance from the art world is understandable given his context: he was untrained, started late, and worked alongside renowned artists. It wasn’t until around the same time Matisse gained recognition that Rousseau began to receive proper acknowledgment. Jan Gordon, in Modern French Painters, notes that while Matisse wanted to avoid clichés, Rousseau’s desire was to paint conventionally enough to be admitted to the Artiste Français.

Time and again, notable thinkers have posited a deep tie between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I contend that at a core level, there's a reason for this. As John Keats penned in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—/ That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of our understanding in life comes from education or experience. Yet, we seem to find ethics and aesthetics appealing without being taught them in these conventional ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are efforts to describe, not prescribe. Our examinations of morality and beauty are usually attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than providing rules for creating or judging good art or moral behavior. More to the point, criticism of art or morals can never fully encapsulate what is good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might revolve around elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these don't explain why it's good art. When asked about a favorite work of art or literature, one often hears a phrase like, "There's just something about it," preceding a more detailed explanation. I believe that both art and morals can't be fully explained by describing their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor states, “A story is a way of saying something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” Similarly, ethics possesses this transcendent quality. As Wittgenstein put it, “Ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / I suggest that it is this 'something,' this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most potent attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them. I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both in a noumenal way, using a Kantian term. They affect us at a level that can be felt but not fully explained. This connection is even stronger in the art of literature. As McKean asserts, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Today's Germany is a formidable nation, bound together by a distinct culture that spans from the alpine peaks of Munich to the Baltic Sea shores of Kiel. This culture is evident from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's heart, to the picturesque city of Dresden along the Elbe. Given this unique cultural tapestry, it's unsurprising that modern Germany is a blend of various sources and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has a name with disputed origins among scholars and historians. Some believe it comes from the Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were once known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to clash with the Gauls. Others propose that "Germanus" was a term used by Julius Caesar to differentiate the Germanic tribes he had not conquered from the Gauls he had, a word he borrowed from the Gauls themselves (Tacitus, 98). Still others suggest the name might be derived from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," indicating the loud and noisy nature of the Germans. (O.E.D., 2010)

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," described the Germans as "aboriginal" and not mixed with other races through immigration or intercourse. He noted that those who sought to emigrate would arrive by sea, and questioned why anyone would leave the comforts of Rome for the harsh climate and customs of Germania (Tacitus, 98).

Meanwhile, the Romans would send their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods and services, and sometimes led military campaigns but generally returned to their sprawling empire. As the Germanic tribes began appearing in the first century, they lived along the Roman Empire's borders, trading their land-based goods and military skills within the Roman army (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

I gazed down at the bowl in front of me, my mind working like a machine, analyzing every detail with cold detachment. It was a scene from a book I'd once bought, "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain," a gift from a painter I'd worked with. The book taught how to frame a complex image into something manageable, like a bowl of fruit on a plain plane. Yet, the sight before me was too much. I could see the influence of great artists - Picasso's blue period, Monet's love for greenery, the Italian Renaissance masters' color palettes. If I could ever claim artistic merit, this was my starting point, my first story, "Work in Brown." My fingers wrapped around my pencil, muscles tensing and releasing as I made my first mark. Water swirled, clear and calm. I could see the shape emerge, but my hand hit the toilet handle again, and nothing happened. The offending package refused to budge, like a slug stuck to the bottom. Mop in hand, tie strangling my neck, I stared at the ugly mess. It took a bit more effort, a few more moments of reflection, and then I was ready, hand wrapped in toilet paper like an oven mitt, dipping into the bowl like a mother retrieving a turkey from the oven...

Teenagers are perishing behind the wheel. A confluence of factors opens up this treacherous route in teen driving statistics. The National Institutes of Health highlight that a key issue is that the teen brain is simply not equipped to handle the perils of driving. Lack of experience also plays a significant role. This inexperience increases the likelihood of fatal accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teenagers also fare poorly when accompanied by peers, a scenario that is common, according to the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center. Their study correlated the passenger's age with the frequency of traffic accidents. Various states have introduced provisional licenses to limit driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers, but these are merely bandaid solutions. The core problem is that, collectively, young drivers are statistically not ready to handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman posits that 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests a common urge among teens under 19-20 to seek thrills, making it logical to delay driving until these tendencies subside. Continuing to grant licenses to young teens will likely lead to an escalating death toll as Baby-Boomers' children become eligible to drive in the coming years. Legislation to address this could involve schools offering driver’s education but not allowing anyone under 18 to operate a vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued before granting a full license, with a set number of training hours required, similar to current state requirements. A national law would uniformly protect teens across the nation. This approach is far from unprecedented.

As I browsed through the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I came across fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films often used creative editing to create illusions. My study of these films generally involved describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the unique characteristics of a few later ones. Early trick films at the turn of the century are typically set-bound, framed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, and use long and medium shots, adhering to the one shot equals one film rule. However, some films from the early twentieth century dared to break these guidelines by incorporating multiple shots.

One common feature among these trick films is their filming in an interior set within a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary, not moving to follow figures or objects. This style, rooted in theatre and vaudeville, means that characters in trick films generally move side-to-side, never walking towards or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth along the horizontal axis, never leaving the frame as the camera doesn't follow them.

The frontal proscenium composition also results in shots that are mostly long and occasionally medium, with close-ups never used. This stems from the theatre tradition, where the audience saw the entire performance at once, framed by the stage's borders. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups are absent.

These early trick films typically follow the rule that one conceptual shot equals one film, limiting most films to about a minute or less. This also restricts their dramatic or narrative use, often focusing on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and switching acts with minimal story. However, keep in mind that one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes doesn't necessarily correspond to one physical shot. A single "shot" might consist of several joined together to create an illusion of apparition or disappearance. For example, observe The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early trick film. A closer look reveals the moment when the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and fervent advocate for Republicanism. Despite being primarily an agriculturalist and having a brief political career, his dedication to these fields shaped his views on personal liberty and government. His passion for the agrarian lifestyle was the cornerstone of his beliefs regarding sovereignty, Constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a sharp decrease in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project, which was quite disheartening. It's tough to pinpoint the exact reason, but the onset of winter in a New England campus likely contributed to the drop in bicycle and pedestrian commuters. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, when everyone is focused on completing schoolwork and processing grades, which might have caused the log submissions to fall off the radar. The month-long holiday break for students and faculty also means many don't need to commute, and classes resuming in late January could explain the low February submissions. Despite these factors, the February slump remains unexplained. It's possible that the project experienced a natural decline in initial excitement, which we tried to combat with the Carpool Challenge Week in March. This blitz campaign did result in an increase in log submissions for March. Maintaining project momentum, especially considering the holiday and semester breaks typical in higher education, proved challenging. Another hurdle was the deep-rooted preference for driving, which prompted the need for incentives. We offered numerous prizes like gift certificates for local restaurants, coffee shops, and even chain stores. However, we wondered if larger prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars could have sparked greater participation. The value of these prizes remained steady throughout the project. If we had announced increased prize values over time, such as adding bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January, participation might have increased instead of decreasing.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that aims to replicate the performance of an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets. Unlike index funds, ETFs trade like stocks on an exchange, offering more flexibility. They provide the diversification benefits of an index fund and the advantages of single stock ownership, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase just one share. Despite these appealing features, ETFs typically have lower expense ratios than mutual funds. However, they come with the downside of incurring commissions on trades, as with buying or selling stocks. ETFs also offer a wide variety of funds to choose from, but it's crucial for savvy investors to assess whether the touted benefits, like diversification, actually exist and to what extent.

For this analysis, we will examine the ETF IHF, comparing it with its top 10 holdings, which represent 63.58% of its assets. Below are the top holdings and their respective percentages.

To gauge how well these top 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can normalize their current asset percentages to 100% and calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion they are held in the ETF. Beta and return calculations are included in the chart below.

From the chart, it is clear that a portfolio comprising only the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, indicating a 16% increase in returns. The Beta of the top 10 holdings is also 0.12 lower than that of the ETF as a whole. These results suggest that a portfolio of just these top 10 stocks could offer a higher return with a lower Beta. However, statistical significance needs to be verified.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Dream-Land, one of Edgar Allan Poe's own self-proclaimed better poems, features the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, a reference traced back to Virgil. Poe was evidently familiar with European literature, as seen in his use of the term, which Virgil employed to describe an island north of Britain, the edge of the known world to the ancient Greeks. Beyond Virgil's usage, some scholars attribute Poe's familiarity with the term "Thule" to his interest in German authors, namely Johann Wolfgang von Goethe.

This connection is significant as it highlights Poe's knowledge of Goethe's work, specifically his drama "Faust," which was first published in two parts: the first in 1808 and the second upon his death in 1832. Within the second part of "Faust," there's a short poem titled "The King of Thule." This poem tells the story of a king who, after losing his wife and giving her a goblet as a gift, descends into heavy drinking and despair. He eventually decides to end his life by throwing the goblet into the sea and walking off a cliff. The similarity between the King of Thule and the speaker in Poe's "Dream-Land" is striking, suggesting a possible connection to Poe's own experiences with loss and alcohol.

Poe utilizes "Thule" twice in his works. In "The Pit and the Pendulum," he mentions "ultma Thule," while in "Dream-Land," he employs the term as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces, with the speaker in "Dream-Land" describing a dark, lonely landscape haunted by the memories of lost friends. This scene mirrors the despair and loneliness of the King of Thule from Goethe's poem, as if Poe stepped into Goethe's world. Goethe was indeed a notable author, and Poe would have been exposed to his work through the many reproductions that circulated after the original publications. Additionally, Poe's admiration for Tennyson would have further drawn him to Goethe's work.

Could a customer injured after slipping on an applesauce spill in a California grocery store be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating the store manager's malicious intent, given that he knew about the spill and failed to clean it for half an hour while eating dinner?

A California judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for punitive damages outright. To prove malice, Palmer must show Martin's actions were deliberately cruel and showed disregard for probable harm. She can argue that Martin should have known about the risk of slips because of previous incidents, but still chose to ignore it. While her argument that Martin was despicable is less convincing, it's still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin failed to take action.

On October 13, 2009, Rich Wayne reported the spill to Martin, who was on a dinner break and didn't have time to clean it up. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin, but he responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before her accident, five similar incidents had occurred in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for damages, and we’re considering filing a motion to dismiss the punitive damage claim.

In California, punitive damages can be awarded for non-contractual acts of oppression, fraud, or malice. (Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a)). Malice is defined as conduct that intended to cause harm or, in the absence of intent, was despicable and committed with willful disregard for others' safety. (id. § 3294(c)(1)). Courts consider conduct malicious if the defendant was aware of the probable danger of their actions and deliberately failed to avoid it. (Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979)).

About four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC. The class sparked heated debates over whether Islam is inherently hostile. This topic feels more pertinent today than ever. Since 9/11, I've witnessed the American media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an unusually tolerant stance. In 2001, it's hard to imagine a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with a clear Muslim background, gaining traction.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography piqued my interest, yet it clashes with my understanding of his character. Traditional accounts portray Muhammad as a conqueror, forcing conversions upon tribes. His biography, however, depicts him as a misunderstood martyr, humbly accepting people's faith. This narrative seems to devalue Muhammad's actions and overshadow Jesus' miracles with similar tales.

The similarities between Jesus' and Muhammad's ministries are striking, particularly the miracle of multiplying mutton and milk. This style of writing suggests Muhammad needed no proof, merely living in truth and miracles. This approach dilutes Jesus' life and miracle, giving credit to Muhammad.

Many stories in the biography seem designed to validate 'witness' conversions, yet they often rely on third-party accounts, diminishing credibility. They portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man, yet historical records contradict this portrayal.

The thing that really bothers me is their attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly figure. If Muslims today knew the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power, it would shed light on this dichotomy.

Every era after Jesus left behind his teachings and beliefs, and Christian thought evolved in a direction that strayed from its origins. Observing this historical trajectory, we notice a persistent drift away from the religion's roots. Today, the world displays a heightened awareness and an unprecedented progressive inclination. While traditionalists persist, they may not significantly impact the broader population. Among Christians, a growing historical consciousness will emerge, fueling a desire to differentiate the doctrines that have accumulated over time from Jesus' original intent. This movement, though slow, is inevitable: it will reverse the trend of Christian history, returning it to its origin. A wave will grow, stripping away layers of doctrine as if rewinding the clock, until only the essence of Jesus' message remains. This reversal will permeate the United States and Europe, encouraging mass adherence to a faith centered solely on Jesus' ideas, with the church leading the charge. However, as the theological clock reverses, the diversity among Christians will diminish, leading to increased uniformity in belief and practice. Regional, denominational, and divisive differences will fade, replaced by growing similarities. History is replete with such reversals. For instance, Christians were initially persecuted by the Roman Empire but later saw its transformation into a Christian state. Our nation transitioned from African-American slavery to equality. This upcoming reversal will unfold within the realm of Christianity, undoing past diversions to return to the source. This shift will be enabled, in part, by interpreting Jesus' teachings metaphorically, not literally. So, what transpired after Jesus' life? If we delve deep into history, we find only Judaism, the theological cradle of Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures lay at its core by the time Rome took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish community was fragmented into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I firmly believe that "The Jungle" showcases the inherent greed and self-interest that lies within human nature. People tend to prioritize their own well-being and strive to improve their lives, often without regard for those less fortunate. The novel demonstrates this through various instances, with the most notable being the factory owners and managers. Their primary objective is to expand and boost their business empires, disregarding any obstacles or collateral damage. Upton Sinclair's description, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," vividly illustrates the detrimental effects of their actions. They display no concern for the people or animals harmed by the pollution or the animal waste run-off from the extensive pens around Packingtown.

The owners and managers also showed no empathy towards their employees, who were mere means to their wealth. They would exploit any opportunity to maximize profits, as Sinclair put it, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They subjected their workers to harsh working conditions and arbitrarily laid off employees without notice or compensation. During this period, workers had little to no legal protection, leaving them vulnerable to the whims of their employers who pushed for increased productivity in grueling environments.

The harsh living and working conditions in Packingtown were so severe that many people worked themselves to the point of exhaustion and death. There were no support systems or agencies to provide information or assistance to workers. Unions were often more exploitative than helpful, profiting from the very workers they were supposed to protect. The workers were essentially trapped in this system, leading to a slave-like existence, as Sinclair wrote, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various tactics to convey specific feelings or attitudes about significant subjects, and some methods are more impactful than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs numerous such techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Occasionally, he pairs adjectives with nouns that wouldn't typically be associated to evoke a certain atmosphere around a subject. At other times, he invests symbols with meaning and then uses them for this purpose. Fitzgerald frequently employs this latter technique with colors, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald endows these colors with significance, particularly white/gray and red/pink, and later uses these meanings to remind readers of certain feelings associated with important objects.

Fitzgerald assigns white/gray the connotation of uniformity, with white representing a more refined and higher social class, and gray signifying something older and faded. He establishes this significance early in the novel with repeated references to these colors. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (page 8), and everyone at Gatsby’s party wears white: Nick wears “white flannels” (page 41), Tom wears a “white shirt” (page 36), and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (page 30). The only time people are not in white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s party: the “halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (page 40). Fitzgerald further emphasizes these colors by coloring many mundane subjects in them: Nick’s commute to work leads him “down the white chasms of lower New York” (page 56), the names of party guests are “gray names” (page 61) on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses” — uniformity (page 28). He also describes ordinary people or places in these colors: Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” (page 19), there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (page 23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (page 26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (page 27).

After imbuing these colors with meaning, Fitzgerald uses them to represent unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects. This technique to show readers something begins with Daisy. After a prolonged absence of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster.” Readers start to see Daisy as less of a character, more like a uniform addition that Gatsby yearns for (page 74). Fitzgerald employs this method consistently around Daisy to evoke the impression of her being an unimportant, uniform addition. For example, her fur collar is a “gray haze” (page 18), and she is again in a “white” (page 115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is an incredibly fertile region, thanks to its mild and sunny climate. Popular crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The demand for organic community-supported agriculture is robust in the area, with many local organizations facing lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations, as well as hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of farm would allow the landowner to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat, offering recreational use, and creating opportunities for farm tours and educational programs. Organic farming can also lead to greater biodiversity of both plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water, although it often comes with higher costs in terms of labor and management. Additionally, practices beneficial to wildlife can add to these costs, such as planting cover crops and managing invasive species. This could make the landowner seek financial assistance or expertise in maximizing both profit and habitat quality. The chosen land is a 160-acre parcel near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It includes chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest, within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan currently includes over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. This area has been home to Native Americans for centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing or wood production for many years. I chose a property from a real estate website and researched available government programs. As a model for farming this land, I located an organic farm in the same area.

Negotiations are deeply influenced by culture, which is more than just what it is, but also what it isn't. It's not uniform, not singular, and not limited to national borders. Generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" oversimplify the reality of cultural nuances. A negotiator should focus on how the cultural context impacts the negotiation, rather than making sweeping assumptions. When venturing into unfamiliar territory, it's natural to compare it to one's own cultural framework, but it's crucial to respect and understand the differences.

Getting to know a culture can mean learning its history, understanding its prejudices, or simply appreciating its customs. Don't aim to change or judge a culture, but rather work within its parameters, especially when you're in a weaker bargaining position. Being in "away" territory means embracing the traditions and beliefs that could be barriers, and using them to move the negotiation forward.

Culture isn't just about national or international differences; it's also about corporate cultures within a nation. Some companies promote long work hours, others emphasize a relaxed schedule. Indicators of corporate culture can be found in employee dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. Even within the same nation, corporate cultures vary greatly. For instance, American corporate culture differs vastly from one company to another, and even within a company, there can be regional differences.

Values are key to understanding a culture as they provide the 'why' behind cultural behaviors. If saving face or communal harmony is valued, a negotiator must be sensitive to not disrespect those values. Conversely, a negotiator from a culture that values hard negotiation tactics may not be eager to settle early. Knowing these generalities before the negotiation begins is important, but also consider your opponent's personal traits to make the negotiation more effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This infamous phrase is found at the outset of Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible, and also serves as the launching point for St. Anselm’s argument on the existence of God, a stance seemingly shared by Thomas Aquinas. To compare their arguments effectively, we’ll start by accepting their shared belief in the Bible’s God. However, neither Anselm nor Aquinas provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

Let’s first break down Anselm’s core argument. He posits that the proof for God's existence lies within our own minds, as God is within our understanding. While his explanation can be convoluted, it essentially boils down to trusting our inherent knowledge of God's existence. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts, as it does not rely on empirical evidence.

Contrarily, Thomas Aquinas proposes that God’s existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence with no need for faith. This approach would be advantageous for evangelism, as it allows for the recruitment of new converts without requiring belief in something unprovable. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support this, each demonstrating the necessity of God's existence in the world.
